+----------------------------------------------------+
| How to run examples under GXTracking/gpu/cuda/test |
+----------------------------------------------------+

1. Assume that a CUDA capable device is available and the toolkit (>= 5.0)
   is installed at /usr/local/cuda 
   
   Otherwise, modify the following line in CMakeLists.txt 
   with an alternative cuda path on your system;

   SET(CUDA_TOOLKIT_ROOT_DIR "/usr/local/cuda") 

2. How to build an example from  GXTracking/gpu/cuda directory

   mkdir bin 
   cd bin
   cmake -DProject=trackingTest2 ..
   make

3. How to run

   3.1 link data (EM tables, Magnetic field map, brem_SB)

   ln -s ../../../data data   

   3.2 run the test engine

   ./trackingTest2 <run_option>

   where <run option>: 0 - default: standard stepping
                       1 - split stepping by GPIL+sorting+DoIt (for GPU)
                       2 - split stepping by GPIL+sorting+DoIt (for GPU and CPU)

   3.3 to run another example, replace the project name (i.e.,trackingTest2) 
       by one of following programs;

       - EMPhysics    (EM processes) - lagacy program with old EM physics
       - geometry     (Navigation) 
       - rngTest      (Random number generation)
       - stepper      (Adaptive step control algorithms)
       - photonTest   (photon physics processes/models)
       - electronTest (electron physics processes/models)
       - dma          (different strategies for memory accesses)
       - soa          (struct of array vs. array of struct)

        example:

        cmake -DProject=stepper ..
        make
        ./stepper [1-3]

4. Other cmake options

   4.1 separate compilation option:
       set(CUDA_SEPARABLE_COMPILATION ON)
   4.2 debug mode
       add "-G -lineinfo" to CUDA_NVCC_FLAGS 
   4.3 Fermi vs. Tesla architecture
       -arch=sm_20 (Fermi - M2090)
       -arch=sm_35 (Tesla - K20M)
